, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Say","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: of Norman origin, a habitational name from Sai in Orne or Say in Indre, France, perhaps so called from a Gaulish personal name <i>Saius</i> + the Latin locative suffix <i>-acum</i> (see also French name 3 below).","English: nickname, perhaps for someone who made or sold say, a type of woollen cloth, or for an habitual wearer of clothes made of this material, from Middle English <i>sai(e)</i> ‘say’ (Old French <i>saie</i>, from Latin <i>saga</i>, plural of <i>sagum</i> ‘military cloak’). See also   Sayer  .","French (southern): topographic name from <i>saix</i> (from Latin <i>saxum</i>) ‘rock’, or a habitational name from a place called with this word, for example, Say in Loire, Saix in Tarn and Vienne, Le Saix in Hautes-Alpes, or Les Saix in Isère."],"variants":[{"name":"Sey","meanings":["English and Scottish: probably a variant of   Say   particularly prevalent in Scotland.","Dutch and Flemish: from a short form of the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Sigiheri</i> (see   Seger  ).","West African (Ghana): Akan (Fante) name of unexplained etymology."]},{"name":"Sayer","meanings":["English: common occupational name from Middle English <i>sayer</i>, a phonetic variant of   Sawyer  , which in Wales and neighboring English counties may have been reinforced by the synonymous Welsh <i>saer</i> ‘carpenter’ and everywhere by a possible borrowing into Middle English of Old French <i>seieor</i>, <i>saieur</i> ‘sawyer’.","English: rare occupational name perhaps denoting an assayer of metals, or a servant who tasted his lord's food before serving, from Middle English <i>saiour</i> ‘assayer, tester’ (a shortened form of Old French <i>assaiour</i>, ultimately from Late Latin <i>exagium</i>, a derivative of <i>exagmināre</i> ‘to weigh’).","English: rare occupational name for a professional reciter or minstrel, from Middle English <i>seier(e)</i> ‘speaker’."]},{"name":"Saye","meanings":["English: variant of   Say  .","Americanized form of Slovenian <b>Saje</b>: nickname for someone with very dark, sooty hair, derived from the root of <i>sajast</i> ‘sooty’, or directly from <i>saja</i> ‘soot’.","West African (Liberia): from the personal name <i>Saye</i>, found among the Mano (Mah) people, denoting a first-born boy."]}]},{"name":"Elizabeth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual spelling of   Elisabeth   in English. It is recorded in the medieval period, but was made popular by being borne by  Queen Elizabeth I  of England (  1533–1603 ). In the 20th century it again became extremely fashionable, partly because it was the name of  Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon  (  1900–2002 ), who in  1936  became Queen Elizabeth as the wife of King George VI, and after his death in  1952  achieved great public affection as Queen Mother for nearly half a century. Even more influentially, it is the name of her daughter  Queen Elizabeth II  (  b. 1926 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Elisabeth","meanings":["The spelling of   Elizabeth   used in the Authorized Version of the New Testament, and in most modern European languages. This was the name of the mother of John the Baptist (Luke 1:60). Etymologically, the name means ‘God is my oath’, and is therefore identical with <i>Elisheba</i>, the name of the wife of Aaron according to the genealogy at Exodus 6:23. The final element seems to have been altered by association with Hebrew <i>shabbāth</i> ‘Sabbath’."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":25,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Elizabeth de Say was born on 24 February 1356 as the daughter of Beatrice de Brewes. She married Sir John de Falvesle of Fawsley, Northants. after 26 July 1382. She died on 8 July 1399, in England, at the age of 43."},"et":{"24 February 1356–8 July 1399":"24. veebruar 1356–8. juuli 1399","1356–1399":"1356–1399","1373–1382":"1373–1382","1350–1404":"1350–1404","–1393":"–1393","1380–1456":"1380–1456","–Female":"Surnud","24 February 1356":"24. veebruar 1356","1373":"1373","Bef 25 Nov 1393":"enne 25. novembrit 1393","1350":"1350","1393":"1393","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","Bef November 1393":"enne novembrit 1393","from 1380 to 1411":"1380 kuni 1411","1404":"1404","Aft 26 Jul 1382":"pärast 26. juulit 1382","1456":"1456","1356":"1356","1399":"1399","8 July 1399":"8. juuli 1399","Winterbourne Clenstone, Dorset, England":"Winterbourne Clenstone, Dorset, England","England":"England"},"fi":{"24 February 1356–8 July 1399":"24. helmikuuta 1356–8. heinäkuuta 1399","1356–1399":"1356–1399","1373–1382":"1373–1382","1350–1404":"1350–1404","–1393":"–1393","1380–1456":"1380–1456","–Female":"Kuollut","24 February 1356":"24. helmikuuta 1356","1373":"1373","Bef 25 Nov 1393":"ennen vuotta 25. marraskuuta 1393","1350":"1350","1393":"1393","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","Bef November 1393":"ennen vuotta marraskuu 1393","from 1380 to 1411":"vuodesta 1380 vuoteen 1411","1404":"1404","Aft 26 Jul 1382":"26. heinäkuuta 1382 jälk